activityGoals.name: Printing the Total Number of Times Elements of One Array Appear in Another Array
activityGoals.goalDescription: Construct a program that has a method that receives two arrays and prints the total number of times the elements in the 2nd array appear in the 1st array. For example, if the 1st array is {1, 2, 3, 3, 4, 4, 5, 6} and the 2nd array is {3, 4, 5, 6, 7}, then the total number of times that the elements in the 2nd array appear in the 1st array is 6.\nNote that we need to count matches for all values in the 2nd array (including duplicate values, if any).
activityGoals.correctOutput: Total number of times the elements in the 2nd list appear in the 1st list is 3

lineList.content: //Step 1.1: Iterate through the values in the 2nd array

commentList: We need variable count to count how many times the elements in the 2nd array appear in the 1st array. We initialize count with 0 because we have not started counting yet.

We want to iterate over the 2nd array (lst2) and count the total number of times its elements appear in the 1st array. To do this, we need use nested for loops. The outer for loop iterates over the elements in the 2nd array while the inner for loop traverses the elements in the 1st array and increments the total number of matches by 1 each time that a match is found between the elements in the two arrays.

activityGoals.name: Creating an array that Contains the Numbers of Times Each Element of One Array Appears in Another Array
activityGoals.goalDescription: Construct a program that has a function that receives two arrays and creates an array that contains the number of times each element in the 2nd array appears in the 1st array. For example, if the 1st array is {1, 2, 3, 3, 4, 4, 5, 6} and the 2nd array is {3, 4, 5, 6, 7}, then the array that contains the number of times each element in the 2nd array appears in the 1st array is {2, 2, 1, 1, 0}.\nAssume that all elements in the 2nd array are unique.

Total matches for 7.0: 0
Total matches for 11.0: 1
Total matches for 3.0: 2
Total matches for 1.0: 0

lineList.content: //Step 1.1: Create an array that we need to store the number of matches

commentList:
We need N variables to store the number of matches for each element in the 2nd list; that means a list is a great way to store this data. Therefore, we need to create a list with the same length as the 2nd list and fill it with 0s as we have not started counting yet. In general, the element at index i in this list will be used for storing the number of times the element at index i in the 2nd list appears in the 1st list.

This statement declares an array variable, counts, creates an array of size lst2.length, and assigns its reference to counts. By default, each number in the array is 0.
lst2.length expression returns the number of elements in the 2nd array (lst2).

lineList.content: //Step 1.2: Iterate through the values in the 2nd array

commentList:
We want to iterate over the indexes in the 2nd array and increment the counter that corresponds to the element at each index every time that we find a match for that element. To do this, we need use nested for loops. The outer for loop iterates over the indexes in the 2nd array while the inner for loop traverses the elements in the 1st array and increments the total number of matches for the elements in the 2nd array each time that a match is found.

This statement is the outer for loop in the nested loop that iterates over the indexes of the 2nd array.

In the first part of the loop header, we define a control variable i and initialize it to 0. In the second part of the loop header, we test whether the control variable has reached the termination threshold. The loop is repeated if the control variable is less than lst2.length and terminates when the control variable reaches lst2.length (lst2.length expression returns the number of elements in the array lst2).

In the third part of the loop header, we increment the control variable by 1 after each iteration of the loop. Note that the first part is executed once before the loop starts, the second part is executed before each iteration, and the third part is executed after each iteration of the loop.
Also note that the increment operator (++) adds 1 to the value of variable i and the result is stored back into the variable i. Therefore, it is functionally equivalent to the statement i = i + 1.
